<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Committee inquiry into the keeping of primates as pets</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Humane Society International/UK submission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> January 2014</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This document forms the submission by Humane Society International/UK to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Environment, Food</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Rural A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffairs Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inquiry into the keeping of primates as pets</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Humane Society International/UK, (HSI UK), is an animal welfare charity which works to fight animal suffering and cruelty and protect animals in distress in the UK, Europe and across</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the world.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Except for those species listed in the Dangerous Wild Animals Act 1976, there is no requirement for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK-based </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private owners of non-human primates to register their animals. Therefore the range of species and numbers of animals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> currently in private ownership in the UK is very poorly understood. There is no system in place that is capable of effectively monitoring the private ownership of non-human primates in the UK.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Non-human primates constitute a large group of highly intellig</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and potentially self-aware </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mammals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with varied and complex </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">physical</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and social needs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are wild animals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have not been domesticated, unlike “traditional” companion animals such as dogs and cats.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The current legislation and Code of Practice rela</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ting to the welfa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re of privately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">kept non-human primates does n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ot and cannot adequately ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">needs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are met</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Additionally, non-human primates represent a potential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">threat to the health and safety</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of humans with who</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> they come into direct or ind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">irect contact.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The collection of some species of non-human primates for the purpose of trade may also present a threat to the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> conservation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">status</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the wild.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Several other countries and jurisdictions, including some EU Member States, have introduced ban</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s or restrictions on the private keeping of non-human primates. Public opinion within the UK, and significant expert and scientific opinion, supports a ban. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SI UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> therefore recommends that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private keeping of non-human primates, and the trade</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">non-human primates for private keeping, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be banned. Given that an unknown number</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of animals are currently in private ownership, HSI UK recommends that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">passage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of a ban is subject to a ‘grandfather clause’ whereby </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">no new primates may come into private ow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nership and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those animals currently in private ownership are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> prevented from breeding, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">registered and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regularly inspected</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through the rest of their natural lives in private ownership using provisions in Sections 13(7) and Section 27 of the Animal Welfare Ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t 2006</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, or transferred to a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sanctua</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ry or other appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> facility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> where their needs can be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">better</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provided for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The extent of the trade and keeping of primates as pets within the UK</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Except for those species listed under the Dangerous Wild Animals Act </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1976</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (DWAA)</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which are s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ubject to licenc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es issued by a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Local Authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, there is currently no requirement for private keepers of non-human primates to register their animals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> species thought to be commonly in private ownership in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, suc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h as marmosets,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tamarins</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and squirrel monkeys,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are not listed under the DWAA. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a consequence, there is little in the way of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">accurate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">information available on the range of species or number of animals currently in private ownership.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 2009, Wild Futures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the RSPCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">conservatively </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estimated the number of non-human primates in private ownership in the UK to be between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2485-7454</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, based on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> survey responses from local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">authorities on numbers of licenc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es issued under the DWAA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">extrapolations to account for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> commonly-held species that were delisted from the DWAA, and assumptions relating to levels of non-compliance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Updated calculations based on the 2012 DWAA license figures result in an increase in the estimates to 3,000-9,000 animals (RSPCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">comm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Si</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nce the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estimates do not consider species that have never been listed under the DWAA, the true number could be far higher</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">framework</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The international commercial trade in wild-caught animals belonging to all primate species is subject to the provi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sions of the Convention on International Trade</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in Endangered Species (CITES) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and associated EU and UK legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">EU Council Regulation (EC) No 338/97</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Control of Trade in Endangered Species (Enforcement) Regulations (COTES)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, respectively), althou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gh these requirements contain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> limited </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provisions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relating to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">animal welfare</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Trade in privately kept non-human primates is largely conducted in private, with breeders and private dealers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> within the UK thought to form</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the principal source</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of animals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, so CI</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TES and the associated national legislation would not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be applicable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in most cases. However,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wild caught or first generation captive-bred </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">animals have been imported into the UK, they should be accompanied by the relevant CITES permits</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Privately kept no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n-human primates in the UK are covered by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Animal Welfare Act 2006 (AWA)</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, by virtue of the fact that they are ‘under the control of man’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as specified in Section 2(b)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The provisions of the AWA which relate to privately kept non-human primates include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Section 4 (‘unnecessary suffering’), Section 9 (‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Duty of person responsible for animal to ensure welfare</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’), and Section 14 (‘Codes of Practice’).</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Code of Practice for the Welfare of Privately Kept Non-Human Primates (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CoP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was published in January 201</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">0.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It seeks to provide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">keepers of non-human primates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">information in order to help them comply with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">requirements of the AWA, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in particular Section 9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and relevant authorities with information to help with enforcement issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in theory </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CoP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is designed to provide information relevant to the 430+ species of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> non-human primate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">so it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is necessarily generic, and cannot hope to provide the detailed information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that would be required to ensure the complex and varied </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">physical, psyc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hological, behavioural and social needs of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> many species</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are covered</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In addition, compliance with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CoP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is not, in and of itself, legally binding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and since there is no registration or licensing requirement for most individual non-human primates in p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rivate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ownership, it is unclear how compliance with a non-binding Code of Practice can be assessed in the majority of cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Surveys of local authorities suggest that many do not use, or are unaware of the existence of, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CoP.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The DWAA lists certain prim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ate species </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in its schedule</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for which a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private keeper requires a licenc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e from the loca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">authority.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The DWAA is principally concerned with the protection of human safety. Some provisions relating to animal welfare do exist, including a requirement that ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commodation, adequate food, drink and bedding, provision for animals in the case of emergency, prevention of spread of disease and space for exercise are provided. Furthermore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a private</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> owner is obliged to obtain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a licence in order to keep animals listed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n the schedule of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the DWAA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which requires a veterinary surgeon or practitioner authorised by the relevant council to carry out an inspection. Licenses last for a two-year period. This inspection regime should, in theory, serve to ensure that legal welfare</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> requirements are adhered to; however there is evidence that the DWAA is far from adequately implemented and enforced, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">questions remain about the training and expertise of veterinary inspectors in primate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">health and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">welfare, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and in any event </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">some of the mo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re commonly kept species, including marmosets,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tamarins</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and squirrel monkeys,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are not covered by the Act.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> So </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">while</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> most species of primate are covered by the DWAA, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> effectiveness of this legislation in protecting the welfare of privately kept non-human </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primates is questionable, and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> majority of individuals held privately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are believed to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">belong to species no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> covered by the legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Non-human</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> primates are wild animal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s and have not been domesticated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, unlike “traditional” companion animals such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dogs and cats.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CoP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, DEFRA describes non-human primates as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘wild undomesticated animals that cannot be house-trained or fully tamed’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘Primates should not be considered as pets in the accepted sense of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">word’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">iv</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Primates have a high capacity to suffer if their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">individual and social </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">needs are not adequately provided for as they have complex brain physiology and advanced cognitive abilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Complaints to the RSPCA relating to non-human primates, as a proportion of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> estimates of numbers of animals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thought to be in private ownership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, are high compared to other commonly-kept pet animal species, and related to animal welfare concerns in around half of all cases. These findings suggest that the welfare of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">privately kept </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is not being adequately protected by current arrangements.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">ii</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sanctuaries such as Wild Futures</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which specialises in the housing and keeping of non-human primates rescued from private ownership, report serious behavioural and health problems in t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he animals they receive.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Commonly-seen issues include lack of socialisation with con-specifics (the RSPCA reports that more than 60% of incidents involving pet primates concerned </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">singly-housed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">animals, in spite of the fact that most primate species exist i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n complex social groups in their natural state), stereotypical behaviours, self-harming, and nutritional disorders. These reports suggest that, at least in the cases seen by sanctuaries such as Wild Futures, the welfare </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">needs of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primates in private ownersh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ip are not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">being adequately provided for.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">ii</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Non-human primates can present a risk to public health. All non-human primates have the potential to carry a range of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">zoonotic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> infectious diseases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> including but not limited to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cercopithecine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">herpesvirus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can be carried by macaques and can cause fatal encephalomyelitis in humans</span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[viii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">), h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">epatitis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, tuberculosis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> intestinal pathogens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and a variety of parasites</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Primates can also inflict injury to people, and their behaviour in captivity can be extremely unpredic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">table</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – according to the Humane Society of the United States more than 260 people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the US</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including many children, have been injured by privately kept non-human primates since 1990, and many more incidents have probably gone unrecorded</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Concerns regardi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng the private keeping of non-human primates remain strong among the public and organisations with expertise in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primatology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and captive primate care.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In a public opinion poll carried out by ICM Research on be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">half of the Captive Animal Protection Society</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Born Free Foundation and The RSPCA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in January-Fe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bruary 2013, 65% of British people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thought th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at the keeping of primates as pets in the UK should be illega</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with just 11% believing it should remain legal</span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[ix]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The four Primate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Advisory Gro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ups of the Associ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation of Zoos and Aquari</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ums</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the United States issued a joint statement supporting the elimination of the trade in pet primates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, on the grounds of risk to anima</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l welfare, species conservation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and public health and safety</span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[x]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In a review published in the s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cientific literature in 2009</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Soulsbury</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> et al stated that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘strong evidence supports the argument that primates are not suitable pets; it is unlikely that the welfare of pet primates can be adequately addressed in normal households’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and concluded that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">he article </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">identiﬁes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> a wide range of concerns about keeping pet primates and concludes that this practice should end’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The Jane </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Goodall</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Institute, the American Veterinary Medical Association</span><a name="_ednref11"></a><a href="#_edn11">[xi]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the American Society of Primatologists, and the National Associ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation of State Public Health Veterinarians all oppose the private possession of primates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A number of countries have already banned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, restricted or regulated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the private keeping of non-human primates, either directly or under legislation concerning the wide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r issue of exotic pet keeping. These include </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Denmark, Bulgaria, Sweden, Belgium, the Netherlands, Switzerland, Canada, the US</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (24 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">US S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tates prohibit the keeping of primates as pets)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Australia, Israel, Mexico and Honduras.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Future restrictions</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">HSI UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">does n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ot believe that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">complex </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">welfare </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and social </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">needs o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f non-human primates can be adequately and consistently met by private owners. Therefore HSI UK supports the introduction of a ban on the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private keeping of and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">trade in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">non-human primates.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt; vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Given the unknown but relatively high number of non-human primates currently in private ownership in the UK, and the limited availability of suitable sanctuary facilities to which to relocate them, HSI UK supports a programme of registration </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for existing a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nimals in private ownership in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oduced using powers granted by Section 13(7) of the AWA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and accompanied by a system of inspection</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> under Section </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">27</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and a ban on breeding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of animals currently in private ownership, and for those </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">remaining </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">animals to live out</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> their natural lives. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where the standard of welfare provided to individuals currently kept is found not to meet the standard </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">currently mandated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by the AWA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> those animals should be removed to identified sanctuaries or other facilities capable of providing t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hem with suitable lifelong care.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10p